        <body>       
                 
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                New York&#44; Oct. 28&#34;87<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I make bold to address<lb/> you a few lines concerning the Semin&#45;<lb/>&#45;ary.  I was to see Dr H. P. Mendes<lb/> yesterday and he stated to me that<lb/> he had written you twice but had<lb/> to his <sic>surprize</sic> up to the hour when<lb/> I saw him not received any answer.<lb/>  He stated that he had sent you a<lb/> letter of Mr Blumenthal&#39;s in which<lb/> was contained the announcement<lb/> that the Board of Trustees had re&#45;<lb/>&#45;solved to open a higher department<lb/> and a request that the Advisory<lb/> Board designate a time for the<lb/> examination and admission of can&#45;<lb/>&#45;didates to both departments and<lb/> also select a preceptor for the newly<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>created higher department.<lb/></p>
            <p>Partly at the desire of Dr Mendes<lb/> who feared that his communications<lb/> had not reached you but mostly of my<lb/> own accord I take the liberty of<lb/> writing you and urging you to<lb/> give the above mentioned matter<lb/> the benefit of your immediate attent&#45;<lb/>&#45;ion.  I believe it absolutely essential<lb/> that the entrance examinations be<lb/> held and the preceptor chosen at as<lb/> early a date as possible.  As regards<lb/> the latter you know my predilection<lb/> and that of most of the advisory<lb/> Board in favor of Dr Lieberman.<lb/>  I am sorry the Trustees did not ad&#45;<lb/>&#45;opt a slightly more liberal compens&#45;<lb/>&#45;ation as I think we can congratulate<lb/> ourselves to secure such an addition<lb/> to our institution.  The more I come<lb/> into contact with Dr Lieberman the<lb/></p> 
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>higher my opinion of him.  He is a<lb/> thoroughly cultured gentleman&#44; entirely<lb/> abreast of the scientific thought of the<lb/> age&#44; a masterly Talmudist and a<lb/> sturdy and consistent Israelite.<lb/></p>
            <p>The best way to bring the matter to<lb/> an issue would be for you to commun&#45;<lb/>icate with him either directly or through<lb/> the secretary of the Advisory Board<lb/> and request him to meet you when<lb/> you could form a judgment of his a&#45;<lb/>bilities.  This could be done before you<lb/> come to New York as Dr Lieberman has<lb/> informed me that he is willing to wait<lb/> upon you in Philadelphia after which he<lb/> would see Dr Kohut.  Dr L&#39;s address is<lb/> 67 East 3<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> St N. Y. C.<lb/></p>
            <p>I would now take the liberty of<lb/> making a request in behalf of my&#45;<lb/>self.  I would very much desire to<lb/> be given a share in the instruction<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>of the higher class in such branches<lb/> as English homiletics&#44; exegesis&#44; history<lb/> Arabic and Syriac which do not strictly<lb/> belong to the new preceptor&#39;s forte or where <del>partly</del><lb/> <del>in order to b</del> two teachers can harmonize&#44; partly to lighten<lb/> his task and partly in order that we may<lb/> both be officially designated preceptors<lb/> of the Seminary without the insidious<lb/> distinction of higher and lower depart&#45;<lb/>ment.  Hoping that Dr L. will be the<lb/> man upon whom the choice falls and<lb/> that you will excuse the frankness<lb/> with which I express my views&#44; since I<lb/> desire only the welfare of the Seminary<lb/> and the blessing to Judaism which shall<lb/> arise from it&#44; I have the honor to be&#44; Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>very sincerely yours<lb/>
                Bernard Drachman<lb/>
                439 E. 56<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/></p>
            </body>
